### C. Explanations:

1. Object Modeling. For this work sample I found it helpful to create a simple model for the data stored for each driver. One of its purposes was to initially create an object with default data for each driver when they were registered by a Driver command.
   An extra minor purpose, which is neat nonetheless, is the **repr** method which allowed a very clean way of printing the final report data in the requested format.
   Another purpose of this class was the ease of access to its attributes by custom get and set methods.

To store and access this information I decided to use Python's built-in dictionary class. The main advantage for using a dictionary is the efficiency when accessing each driver's values. Since Trip commands are not guaranteed to be consecutive, it means that using each driver's name as a key in a dictionary (or map in other langs) will allow for efficient access to each driver's data every time. If I used a list, I would have to iterate through that list multiple times for each command to find a registered driver or to verify whether a driver has been registered yet, or I would have to keep track of the list's indices in association with drivers' names in a different structure and that's where the dictionary came in.

2. Testing. What I found really important was to make sure to skip lines that would cause any unwanted changes to the final data. Throughout the code I have checks the will cause a line to be skipped if certain requirements are not met.
   I have added multiple tests to check validity of input that run before the main function is executed.
   The requirements I ended up with are the following:
   a. To make sure initial data is controlled
